OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F469A1776957067
OL,3,CWhat happens if the largest party in
OL,4,CSenedd election falls short of a
OL,5,Cmajority?
OL,7,FSo what happens if Reform UK becomes
OL,8,Fthe largest party in a few weeks'
OL,9,Ftime, but falls short of an overall
OL,10,Fmajority? That could open the door for
OL,11,Fother parties to club together and
OL,12,Fform a coalition to ensure Wales
OL,13,Fdoesn't see a Reformer government.
OL,15,FOur poll asked people if it would be
OL,16,Ffair for a government to be formed,
OL,17,Fwithout including the largest party
OL,18,F(something which regularly happens in
OL,19,Fmany democracies across Europe).
OL,1,Wj5hw}j5 ~shws                   G6/9
OL,2,W+.-'*%/"-$+,(,'T(,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BWales News CReg TV FThis Day
FL,495,460,260,120,000,100
PN,46907
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F469A1776957067
OL,3,CWhat happens if the largest party in
OL,4,CSenedd election falls short of a
OL,5,Cmajority?
OL,7,FResponses were evenly split with 31%
OL,8,Fsaying it would be fair, 30% saying it
OL,9,Fwould be unfair and the rest replying
OL,10,Feither "neither" or "don't know."
OL,12,FInterestingly, when we gave people the
OL,13,Fsame hypothetical scenario but named
OL,14,FReform UK as the largest party,
OL,15,Fopinions changed somewhat, with the
OL,16,Fnumber of people claiming it would be
OL,17,Ffair to keep them out of power
OL,18,Fincreasing six points to 37%.
OL,26,@rD@HOUrD@PO]rD@UOUrD@aO]
OL,1,Wj5hw}j5 ~shws                   G7/9
